OL,3,CD-Day veteran calls for sacrifice of
OL,4,Clife to be recognised by future
OL,5,Cgenerations
OL,7,FOn June 6 1944, D-Day, also known as
OL,8,FOperation Overlord, marked the
OL,9,Fbeginning of the end of the Second
OL,10,FWorld War, as more than 150,000 Allied
OL,11,Ftroops launched a massive beach
OL,12,Fassault on the coast of Normandy by
OL,13,Fair and sea.
OL,15,FA total of 4,414 Allied troops were
OL,16,Fkilled and more than 5,000 wounded.
OL,18,FMr Lamond recalled taking part as an
OL,19,F18-year-old seaman, a year after
OL,20,Fjoining the Royal Navy.
OL,1,Wz5~k4~k7}hw1 ~k4~sj5j5~s1 G     G2/10
